    "body": "### Description\n\nHowdy, I'm a new user, so feel free to tell me to file this elsewhere. I'm using `lazy.nvim` to set this up, and it works perfectly the first time I start LSP (`LspInfo`):\n\n```\nvim.lsp: Active Clients ~\n- hls (id: 1)\n  - Version: ? (no serverInfo.version response)\n  - Root directory: ~/dev/haskell/haskell-language-server\n  - Command: { \"haskell-language-server\", \"--lsp\", \"--debug\" }\n  - Settings: {\n      haskell = {\n        cabalFormattingProvider = \"cabal-gild\",\n        formattingProvider = \"fourmolu\"\n      }\n    }\n  - Attached buffers: 25\n```\n\nHowever, once I run `LspRestart` the command is restored to the default:\n```\nvim.lsp: Active Clients ~\n- hls (id: 2)\n  - Version: ? (no serverInfo.version response)\n  - Root directory: ~/dev/haskell/haskell-language-server\n  - Command: { \"haskell-language-server-wrapper\", \"--lsp\" }\n  - Settings: {\n      haskell = {\n        cabalFormattingProvider = \"cabalfmt\",\n        formattingProvider = \"ormolu\"\n      }\n    }\n  - Attached buffers: 25\n```\n\nNotice the difference in Command and Settings. More context, I'm using `lazy.nvim` to configure this, so feel free to tell me to ask there. Here's how I set my config:\n```\nreturn {\n  \"neovim/nvim-lspconfig\",\n  priority = 1000,\n  lazy = false,\n\n  config = function(_, opts)\n    vim.lsp.set_log_level('debug')\n\n    require('lspconfig')['hls'].setup{\n      filetypes = { 'haskell', 'lhaskell' },\n      cmd = { \"haskell-language-server\", \"--lsp\", \"--debug\" };\n      settings = {\n        haskell = {\n          cabalFormattingProvider = \"cabal-gild\",\n          formattingProvider = \"fourmolu\",\n        },\n      },\n    }\n  end,\n}\n```",
